b Dems'']\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050421235235/http://comment.independent.co.uk/columnists_a_l/bruce_anderson/story.jsp?story=630808 ''Independent'' story on the 2005 campaign]\n* [http://www.wbca.org.uk/ West Berkshire Conservative Association]\n* [http://www.davidrendel.org.uk/ David Rendel's Official Homepage]\n* [http://www.labour-southeast.org.uk Labour South East]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080307072911/http://www.election-maps.co.uk/ ]\n* [http://www.uk-genealogy.org.uk/images/maps/Berkshire.jpg Map of old Berkshire Constituency]\n\n{{Constituencies in South East England}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Newbury (Uk Parliament Constituency)}}\n[[Category:Parliamentary constituencies in Berkshire]]\n[[Category:Newbury, Berkshire|*]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom Parliamentary constituencies established in 1885]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=February 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox UK constituency main\n |name        = Newbury\n |parliament  = uk\n |map1        = Newbury2007\n |map2        = EnglandBerkshire\n |map_entity  = [[Berkshire]]\n |map_year    =\n |year        = 1885\n |abolished   =\n |type        = County\n |previous    = [[Berkshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Berkshire]]\n |next        =\n |electorate  = 82,034 (2018)<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://boundarycommissionforengland.independent.gov.uk/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/England-Parliamentary-electorates-for-2018.xlsx \n |title=England Parliamentary electorates 2010-2018\n |publisher=Boundary Commission for England \n |accessdate=23 March 2019\n |df=dmy \n}}</ref>\n |mp          = [[Laura Farris]]\n |party       = [[Conservative]]\n |region      = England\n |county      = [[Berkshire]]\n |european    = South East England\n |towns       = [[Newbury, Berkshire|Newbury]], [[Thatcham]], [[Hungerford]]\n |elects_howmany = One\n}}\n'''Newbury''' is a [[List of United Kingdom Parliament constituencies|constituency]]{{#tag:ref|A [[county constituency]] (for the purposes of election expenses and type of returning officer)|group= n}} represented in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] of the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|UK Parliament]] from 2019 by [[Laura Farris]], a Conservative.{{#tag:ref|As with all constituencies, the constituency elects one Member of Parliament (MP) by the [[first past the post]] system of election at least every five years.|group= n}} It was created by the [[Redistribution of Seats Act 1885]] and has been in continual existence since then.\n\n==Profile==\nThe constituency consists of most of [[West Berkshire]] and includes [[Newbury, Berkshire|Newbury]], [[Thatcham]] and [[Hungerford]].  To the east, the rest of West Berkshire is incorporated into the [[Wokingham (UK Parliament constituency)|Wokingham]] and [[Reading West (UK Parliament constituency)|Reading West]] constituencies.{{#tag:ref|Burghfield, Mortimer and Sulhamstead; and, respectively Burch Copse, Calcot, Pangbourne, Purley on Thames, Theale and Westwood|group= n}}\n\nSince its creation it has been a [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] or [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]]/[[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] seat, sometimes seemingly [[marginal seat|marginal]] and sometimes seen as a [[safe seat]], with a tendency towards being Conservative.{{#tag:ref|The total period served by either a Liberal or Liberal Democrat MP is 17 years, Conservative MPs have served for the remaining 110 years (to the end of 2012)|group= n}}  West Berkshire which is similar to its neighbours has a rather thriving economy with the headquarters of the communications company [[Vodafone]] that has created a cluster of around 80 mobile phone related businesses in Newbury,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.westberks.gov.uk/CHttpHandler.ashx?id=26989&p=0|title=West Berkshire Council - Can't Find Page|website=www.westberks.gov.uk}}</ref> while the [[Lambourn]] area is the second most important centre for the racehorse industry in Great Britain, employing over 800 people directly, and producing an annual income of \u00a320 million.<ref>[http://www.northwessexdowns.org.uk/wba/nwd-aonb/NWDWebsiteV3.nsf/$LUcontent/2.4?OpenDocument ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120717034847/http://www.northwessexdowns.org.uk/wba/nwd-aonb/NWDWebsiteV3.nsf/$LUcontent/2.4?OpenDocument |date=17 July 2012 }}</ref>\n\nWest Berkshire is also home to [[Atomic Weapons Establishment]], near [[Aldermaston]], [[Wolseley plc]], [[Bayer]] and [[Pepsico]]. There are high proportions of detached and semi-detached housing, and lower than average dependency on [[social housing]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ons.gov.uk/help/localstatistics|title=Local statistics - Office for National Statistics|website=www.ons.gov.uk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/guide-method/census/2011/census-data/2011-census-interactive-content/index.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160129132219/http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/guide-method/census/2011/census-data/2011-census-interactive-content/index.html|url-status=dead|title=2011 census interactive maps|archivedate=29 January 2016}}</ref>  The seat includes the former family home of [[Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge]], wife of [[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge]] in [[Bucklebury]].\n\n;Neighbouring constituencies\nThe constituencies bordering Newbury (clockwise from north) are: [[Wantage (constituency)|Wantage]], [[Henley (constituency)|Henley]], [[Reading West (UK Parliament constituency)|Reading West]], [[Wokingham (constituency)|Wokingham]], [[Basingstoke (UK Parliament constituency)|Basingstoke]], [[Hampshire North West (UK Parliament constituency)|North West Hampshire]] and [[Devizes (UK Parliament constituency)|Devizes]].\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Newbury1954.png|thumb|right|150px|The Newbury constituency in 1954]]\nOriginally, Newbury was part of a larger constituency of [[Berkshire]], which returned two Members of Parliament (MPs), increased to three in the [[Reform Act 1832|Reform Act of 1832]]. In the [[Redistribution of Seats Act 1885|Redistribution of Seats Act of 1885]] Berkshire was divided into three county constituencies, [[Abingdon (UK Parliament constituency)|Northern (Abingdon)]], Southern (Newbury), and [[Wokingham (UK Parliament constituency)|Eastern (Wokingham)]], and two [[borough constituency|borough constituencies]], [[Reading (UK Parliament constituency)|Reading]] and [[Windsor (UK Parliament constituency)|New Windsor]], each returning one member.\n\nThe [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]] have held the constituency for all but seventeen years since the creation of the seat - only three spells of [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]], or [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]], majorities have intersected their control. In [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]], the party held the largest majority in the seat since [[1935 United Kingdom general election|1935]] at 46%, before being reduced to 40.1% in [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017]].\n\nSince the [[February 1974 United Kingdom general election|February 1974 election]], the Liberal Democrats have been one of the two largest parties in the constituency. They most recently gained the seat at the [[1993 Newbury by-election|1993 by-election]], holding it until [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]] where it was regained by the Conservatives.\n\nThe constituency in 2010 produced the third lowest share of the vote for [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] (4.3%), one of five lost deposits for Labour nationally, below the 5% of the vote deposit threshold.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/elections/results/general_elections|title=General Election Results from the Electoral Commission}}</ref>{{#tag:ref|Other lost Labour deposits took place in Eastbourne, Somerton & Frome, Cornwall North and Westmorland & Lonsdale|group= n}} In 2017, Labour earned its highest share of the vote in Newbury since the [[October 1974 United Kingdom general election|October 1974 election]] with 14.1% of the vote.\n\nIt was estimated that the constituency voted 51% in favour of remaining in the European Union during the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 referendum on EU membership]], with 49% voting to leave.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.electoralcalculus.co.uk/cgi-bin/seatdetails.py?seat=Newbury|title=Newbury|work=Electoral Calculus|accessdate=5 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{for|European Elections|Newbury, Berkshire}}\n\n== Boundaries and boundary changes ==\n[[File:Newbury election results (smaller).png|right|thumb|320x320px|A graph plotting the election results for Newbury.([[:File:Newbury election results.png|larger version and key]])]]\n'''1885\u20131918''': The constituency was created as the Southern or Newbury Division of Berkshire under the [[Redistribution of Seats Act 1885]], when the three-member Parliamentary County of [[Berkshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Berkshire]] was divided into the three single-member constituencies of [[Abingdon (UK Parliament constituency)|Abingdon,]] Newbury and [[Wokingham (UK Parliament constituency)|Wokingham.]] It comprised the Boroughs of Newbury and Reading, the Sessional Divisions of Ilsley, Lambourn, Newbury (including Hungerford), and Reading (except the parishes of East Swallowfield and West Swallowfield), and part of the Sessional Division of Wokingham.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://archive.org/details/publicgeneralac01walegoog|title=The public general acts|last=Great Britain|first=Incorporated Council of Law Reporting for England and Wales|publisher=Proprietors of the Law Journal Reports, 1884|others=unknown library|language=English}}</ref>  Only non-resident freeholders of the municipal borough Reading (which comprised the Parliamentary Borough of [[Reading (UK Parliament constituency)|Reading]]) were entitled to vote.\n\n'''1918\u20131950''': The Boroughs of Newbury and Wokingham, the Rural Districts of Hungerford and Newbury, and parts of the Rural Districts of Bradfield and Wokingham.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite book|title=Boundaries of parliamentary constituencies 1885-1972;|last=S.|first=Craig, Fred W.|date=1972|publisher=Political Reference Publications|isbn=0900178094|location=Chichester|oclc=539011}}</ref>\n\nExtended eastwards, with the addition of Wokingham and surrounding areas from the abolished Wokingham Division of Berkshire.  Small northern part transferred to Abingdon and areas which had been annexed by Reading County Borough transferred to the Parliamentary Borough.\n\n'''1950\u20131955''': The Borough of Newbury, and the Rural Districts of Bradfield, Hungerford, and Newbury.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\nWokingham and rural areas to the south and east of Reading transferred to the re-established County Constituency of Wokingham.  Small area transferred from Abingdon.\n\n'''1955\u20131974''': The Borough of Newbury, the Rural Districts of Bradfield, Hungerford, and Newbury, and the County Borough of Reading ward of Tilehurst.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\nGained the Tilehurst ward from the abolished Borough Constituency of [[Reading North (UK Parliament constituency)|Reading North]].  From the 1964 general election, the Reading wards of Norcot and Tilehurst were included<ref name=\":02\" /> following a revision to the local authority wards.\n\n'''1974\u20131983''': As 1950.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\nThe Norcot and Tilehurst wards transferred back to the re-established Borough Constituency of Reading North.\n\n'''1983\u20131997''': The District of Newbury wards of Aldermaston, Basildon, Beenham, Bradfield, Bucklebury, Burghfield, Chieveley, Cold Ash, Compton, Craven, Downlands, Falkland, Greenham, Hungerford, Kintbury, Lambourn Valley, Mortimer, Northcroft, St John's, Shaw-cum-Donnington, Speen, Thatcham North, Thatcham South, Thatcham West, Turnpike, and Winchcombe.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/1983/417/contents/made/data.htm|title=The Parliamentary Constituencies (England) Order 1983|website=www.legislation.gov.uk|access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref>\n\nGained a small area of the abolished County Constituency of Abingdon (part of the former Rural District of Wantage) which had been retained by Berkshire when the rest of the area comprising Abingdon was transferred to Oxfordshire by the [[Local Government Act 1972]].  Areas to the west of Reading included in the new County Constituency of [[Reading West (UK Parliament constituency)|Reading West.]]\n\n'''1997\u20132010''': The District of Newbury wards of Aldermaston, Basildon, Beenham, Bradfield, Bucklebury, Chieveley, Cold Ash, Compton, Craven, Downlands, Falkland, Greenham, Hungerford, Kintbury, Lambourn Valley, Northcroft, St John's, Shaw-cum-Donnington, Speen, Thatcham North, Thatcham South, Thatcham West, Turnpike, and Winchcombe.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/1995/1626/made/data.htm|title=The Parliamentary Constituencies (England) Order 1995|website=www.legislation.gov.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref>\n\nSmall loss to Wokingham in the east of the constituency (Burghfield and Mortimer wards).\n\n'''2010\u2013present''': The District of West Berkshire wards of Aldermaston, Basildon, Bucklebury, Chieveley, Clay Hill, Cold Ash, Compton, Downlands, Falkland, Greenham, Hungerford, Kintbury, Lambourn Valley, Northcroft, St John's, Speen, Thatcham Central, Thatcham North, Thatcham South and Crookham, Thatcham West, and Victoria.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2007/1681/made/data.htm|title=The Parliamentary Constituencies (England) Order 2007|website=www.legislation.gov.uk|access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref>\n\nFurther minor loss to Wokingham.\n\n==Changes proposed by the Boundary Commission==\nThe [[Boundary Commission for England]] submitted their final proposals in respect of the [[Sixth Periodic Review of Westminster constituencies|Sixth Periodic Review of Westminster Constituencies]] (the 2018 review) in September 2018 which would reduce the total number of MPs from 650 to 600. Although the proposals were immediately laid before [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] they were not brought forward by the [[Government of the United Kingdom|Government]] for approval. Accordingly, they will '''not''' come into effect for the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 election]] due to take place on 12 December 2019, which will be contested using the constituency boundaries in place since 2010.\n\nThe Commission proposed that two [[West Berkshire|District of West Berkshire]] wards ([[Basildon, Berkshire|Basildon]] and [[Bucklebury]]) be transferred to [[Reading West (UK Parliament constituency)|Reading West]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bce2018.org.uk/publications|title=Final recommendations report|last=Boundary Commission for England, 2018 Review, Associated consultation documents|date=September 2018|website=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190215215741/https://www.bce2018.org.uk/publications|archive-date=15 February 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Members of Parliament==\nAn incumbent MP has been defeated just four times, in the elections of [[1906 United Kingdom general election|1906]], [[1923 United Kingdom general election|1923]], [[1924 United Kingdom general election|1924]], and [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]].\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n!colspan=2|Election!!Member<ref>{{Rayment-hc|n|1|date=March 2012}}</ref>!!Party\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" | || 1885 || [[William George Mount]] || [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" | || 1900 || [[Sir William Mount, 1st Baronet|William Mount]] || [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Liberal Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" | || 1906 || [[Frederick Coleridge Mackarness]] || [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" | || 1910 || [[Sir William Mount, 1st Baronet|William Mount]] || [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" | || 1922 || [[Howard Clifton Brown]] || [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Liberal Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" | || 1923 || [[Harold Stranger]] || [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" | || 1924 || [[Howard Clifton Brown]] || [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" | || 1945 || [[Anthony Hurd]] || [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" | || 1964 || [[John Astor]] || [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" | || Feb 1974 || Sir [[Michael McNair-Wilson]] || [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" | || 1992 || [[Judith Chaplin]] || [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\" | || 1993 by-election || [[David Rendel]] || [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" | || 2005 || rowspan=\"3\" |[[Richard Benyon]] || [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Independent politician/meta/color}}\" | || rowspan=\"2\" | ''2019'' || [[Independent politician|Independent]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n|[[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: {{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" | \n|2019\n|[[Laura Farris]]\n|[[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n|}\n\n==Elections==\n\n===Elections in the 2010s===\n\n{{Electio