rvative Party (UK)\n  |swing      =\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\nAfter the 1970 general election, Newbury's boundaries were altered to reduce the size of the electorate which had grown to over 85,000. After the boundary changes, the electorate numbered around 72,000 people. This came into effect for the first general election in February 1974.\n\n{{Election box begin | title=[[1970 United Kingdom general election|General election 1970]]: Newbury}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Conservative Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = [[John Astor]]\n  |votes = 30,380 | percentage = 48.8 | change = +3.5\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Timothy Sims\n  |votes = 18,647 | percentage = 29.9 | change = \u22128.1\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Dane Clouston\n  |votes = 13,279 | percentage = 21.3 | change = +4.6\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n  |votes = 11,733 | percentage = 18.9 | change = +11.7\n}}\n{{Election box turnout|\n  |votes = 55,392 | percentage = 72.6 | change  = \u22126.5\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link|\n  |winner     = Conservative Party (UK)\n  |swing      =\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n===Elections in the 1960s===\n{{Election box begin | title=[[1966 United Kingdom general election|General election 1966]]: Newbury}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Conservative Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = [[John Astor]]\n  |votes = 25,908 | percentage = 45.3 | change = \u22120.1\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Ronald Spiller\n  |votes = 21,762 | percentage = 38.0 | change = +3.6\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link|\n  |party      = Liberal Party (UK)\n  |candidate  = Stanley Clement Davies\n  |votes = 9,571 | percentage = 16.7 | change = \u22123.5\n}}\n{{Election box majority|\n  |votes = 4,146 | percent