{"title_page": "Cherylee Houston", "text_new": "{{short description|British actress|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=February 2017}}\n{{More footnotes|date=May 2010}}\n}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Cherylee Houston\n| image              = \n| birth_name         = Cherylee Anne Houston\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1974|8|20|df=y}} \n| birth_place        = [[Morecambe]], [[Lancashire]], England\n| death_date         = \n| othername          = \n| occupation         = Actress\n| years_active       = 2003\u2013present\n| partner            = [[Toby Hadoke]]\n| website            = \n}}\n\n'''Cherylee Houston''' (born 20 August 1974<ref>[https://origin-www.thegazette.co.uk/company/02312426/filing-history/MDA0ODA2MDQyN2FkaXF6a2N4 Annual-Return - The Gazette]</ref>) is a British actress. She grew up in [[Morecambe]], [[Lancashire]], in the [[United Kingdom]]. She is currently playing [[Izzy Armstrong]] in ''[[Coronation Street]]'', a role she has portrayed since April 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/soaps/coronation-street/a214077/coronation-street-family-given-new-surname/|title='Coronation Street' family given new surname|work=[[Digital Spy]]|accessdate=20 April 2020|first=Kris|last=Green|date=13 April 2010}}</ref> She also plays Maz in the ongoing radio 4 series Tinsel Girl.\n\n==Early life==\nHouston's parents, Bill and Coral, ran their own [[photography]] business. She has two older brothers Lee and Vincent. Her love for entertainment began at the age of seven after she watched the film ''[[Annie (1982 film)|Annie]]''.{{Citation needed|date=July 2017}} As a teenager she began appearing in school plays and later trained at the [[Arden School of Theatre]] in [[Manchester]]. It was only after she graduated at 23 that she was diagnosed with the rare connective tissue disorder, [[Ehlers-Danlos syndrome]], Type III [[Hypermobility (joints)|hypermobility]] type. She has used a [[wheelchair]] ever since.{{Citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\n==Career==\nIn 2003 she landed a part in the daytime TV soap ''[[Doctors (2000 TV series)|Doctors]]'', playing a girl with [[multiple sclerosis]]. More TV work followed, including appearances in ''[[The Bill]]'', ''[[Holby City]]'', ''[[Emmerdale]]'' and the cult comedy series ''[[Little Britain]]'', where she played the girlfriend of wheelchair-user [[Andy Pipkin]], played by [[Matt Lucas]]. In 2006 she was one of the main characters in the BBC3 comedy ''[[I'm with Stupid (TV series)|I'm with Stupid]]'' playing Dorothy. In 2010 she landed the part of [[Izzy Armstrong]] in ''[[Coronation Street]]''. \nFrom 2015 she has played Maz in the radio 4 drama series Tinsel Girl. There have been three week-long series: TG and the Tropical Island, where she has to fund raise to get to a friend's wedding in the Seychelles;<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b050xkyy</ref> TG and the Reunion, where she falls out with a long-time friend after discovering that she was asked to be-friend her at uni because she was disabled;<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/sounds/play/b07m58fc</ref> TG and the Support Worker where Maz comes to terms with needing and hiring a support worker/ carer whilst keeping her part-time job at a theatre box office.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/sounds/play/b08pdzxn</ref> There has also been a one-off 45 minute drama featuring Maz at a chronic pain clinic, first broadcast 30 August 2019.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/sounds/play/m0007ymd</ref> All of these were written by Lou Ramsden and produced by Charlotte Riches. They are partially based on incidents in Cherylee's life. Maz shares her diagnosis of EDS, dislocations and chronic pain.\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/celebs/news/2010/05/21/cherylee-houston-makes-history-as-coronation-street-s-first-disabled-actress-115875-22276037/ |title=Cherylee Houston makes history as Coronation Street's first disabled actress |publisher=Mirror |date=2010-05-21 |first=Sue |last=Crawford |accessdate=2010-06-20}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.amberltd.co.uk/main/actor.aspx?actor_refno=70 |title=Cherylee Houston |publisher=Amber Personal Management Ltd |date= |accessdate=2010-06-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090603003157/http://www.amberltd.co.uk/main/actor.aspx?actor_refno=70 |archivedate=2009-06-03 |df= }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|id=1736239|name=Cherylee Houston}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Houston, Cherylee}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English television actresses]]\n[[Category:English soap opera actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Lancashire]]\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:People with Ehlers\u2013Danlos syndrome]]\n[[Category:English people with disabilities]]\n[[Category:People from Morecambe]]\n\n\n{{screen-actor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British actress|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=February 2017}}\n{{More footnotes|date=May 2010}}\n}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Cherylee Houston\n| image              = \n| birth_name         = Cherylee Anne Houston\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1974|8|20|df=y}} \n| birth_place        = [[Morecambe]], [[Lancashire]], England\n| death_date         = \n| othername          = \n| occupation         = Actress\n| years_active       = 2003\u2013present\n| partner            = [[Toby Hadoke]]\n| website            = \n}}\n\n'''Cherylee Houston''' (born 20 August 1974<ref>[https://origin-www.thegazette.co.uk/company/02312426/filing-history/MDA0ODA2MDQyN2FkaXF6a2N4 Annual-Return - The Gazette]</ref>) is a British actress. She grew up in [[Morecambe]], [[Lancashire]], in the [[United Kingdom]]. She is currently playing [[Izzy Armstrong]] in ''[[Coronation Street]]'', a role she has portrayed since April 2010.{{Citation needed|date=July 2017}} She also plays Maz in the ongoing radio 4 series Tinsel Girl.\n\n==Early life==\nHouston's parents, Bill and Coral, ran their own [[photography]] business. She has two older brothers Lee and Vincent. Her love for entertainment began at the age of seven after she watched the film ''[[Annie (1982 film)|Annie]]''.{{Citation needed|date=July 2017}} As a teenager she began appearing in school plays and later trained at the [[Arden School of Theatre]] in [[Manchester]]. It was only after she graduated at 23 that she was diagnosed with the rare connective tissue disorder, [[Ehlers-Danlos syndrome]], Type III [[Hypermobility (joints)|hypermobility]] type. She has used a [[wheelchair]] ever since.{{Citation needed|date=July 2017}}\n\n==Career==\nIn 2003 she landed a part in the daytime TV soap ''[[Doctors (2000 TV series)|Doctors]]'', playing a girl with [[multiple sclerosis]]. More TV work followed, including appearances in ''[[The Bill]]'', ''[[Holby City]]'', ''[[Emmerdale]]'' and the cult comedy series ''[[Little Britain]]'', where she played the girlfriend of wheelchair-user [[Andy Pipkin]], played by [[Matt Lucas]]. In 2006 she was one of the main characters in the BBC3 comedy ''[[I'm with Stupid (TV series)|I'm with Stupid]]'' playing Dorothy. In 2010 she landed the part of [[Izzy Armstrong]] in ''[[Coronation Street]]''. \nFrom 2015 she has played Maz in the radio 4 drama series Tinsel Girl. There have been three week-long series: TG and the Tropical Island, where she has to fund raise to get to a friend's wedding in the Seychelles;<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b050xkyy</ref> TG and the Reunion, where she falls out with a long-time friend after discovering that she was asked to be-friend her at uni because she was disabled;<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/sounds/play/b07m58fc</ref> TG and the Support Worker where Maz comes to terms with needing and hiring a support worker/ carer whilst keeping her part-time job at a theatre box office.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/sounds/play/b08pdzxn</ref> There has also been a one-off 45 minute drama featuring Maz at a chronic pain clinic, first broadcast 30 August 2019.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/sounds/play/m0007ymd</ref> All of these were written by Lou Ramsden and produced by Charlotte Riches. They are partially based on incidents in Cherylee's life. Maz shares her diagnosis of EDS, dislocations and chronic pain.\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/celebs/news/2010/05/21/cherylee-houston-makes-history-as-coronation-street-s-first-disabled-actress-115875-22276037/ |title=Cherylee Houston makes history as Coronation Street's first disabled actress |publisher=Mirror |date=2010-05-21 |first=Sue |last=Crawford |accessdate=2010-06-20}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.amberltd.co.uk/main/actor.aspx?actor_refno=70 |title=Cherylee Houston |publisher=Amber Personal Management Ltd |date= |accessdate=2010-06-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090603003157/http://www.amberltd.co.uk/main/actor.aspx?actor_refno=70 |archivedate=2009-06-03 |df= }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|id=1736239|name=Cherylee Houston}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Houston, Cherylee}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English television actresses]]\n[[Category:English soap opera actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Lancashire]]\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:People with Ehlers\u2013Danlos syndrome]]\n[[Category:English people with disabilities]]\n[[Category:People from Morecambe]]\n\n\n{{screen-actor-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Conquistador2k6", "label": "safe", "comment": "source", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cherylee_Houston"}
{"title_page": "Judah Lewis", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Judah Lewis\n| image              = Judah Lewis on BTVR.jpg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = Lewis discusses ''[[Demolition (2015 film)|Demolition]]'' in 2016\n| birth_date         = {{circa|{{Birth based on age as of date|17|2018|11|22}}}}<ref name=\"thr\">{{cite news |title=Judah Lewis on Working With Kurt Russell for 'Christmas Chronicles' and Why It Isn't Just a \"Kids Movie\" |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/judah-lewis-discusses-working-kurt-russell-christmas-chronicles-1163160 |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |language=en}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = \n| nationality        = American\n| occupation         = Actor\n| years_active       = 2014\u2013present\n| known_for          = \n| height             = \n| notable_works      = {{plainlist|\n* ''[[Demolition (2015 film)|Demolition]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[The Babysitter (2017 film)|The Babysitter]]'' (2017)\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Judah Lewis''' (born {{circa|{{Birth based on age as of date|17|2018|11|22|noage=1}}}})<ref name=\"thr\" /> is an American actor, known for roles in the films ''[[The Babysitter (2017 film)|The Babysitter]]'', ''[[Summer of 84]]'', ''[[Deliverance Creek]]'' and ''[[Demolition (2015 film)|Demolition]]'', and a recurring role in the 2016 television series ''[[Game of Silence (U.S. TV series)|Game of Silence]]''.\n\n== Life and career ==\nLewis is the son of Hara and Mark Lewis, who are acting teachers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thejewishnews.com/2017/10/11/33207/|title=Celebrity Jews, Hollywood, Movies and more |last1=Bloom|first1=Nate|work=The Jewish News|date=2017-10-11 |accessdate=2019-11-10}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2015, Lewis was among the six actors who screen tested for the lead role (which went to [[Tom Holland (actor)|Tom Holland]]) in the 2017 reboot film ''[[Spider-Man: Homecoming]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/spider-man-hopefuls-screen-test-798995 |title=Spider-Man Hopefuls Screen-Test in Atlanta as Marvel Decision Nears |last1=Kit |first1=Borys |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=2015-05-30 |accessdate=2017-09-09}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Lewis appeared in the drama film ''[[Demolition (2015 film)|Demolition]]'', opposite [[Jake Gyllenhaal]] and [[Naomi Watts]] and the action thriller remake ''[[Point Break (2015 film)|Point Break]]'', appearing briefly as the young version of the lead character, Johnny Utah.\n\nIn 2015, Lewis filmed the role of a boy hunted by his babysitter, played by [[Samara Weaving]], in the comedy horror film ''[[The Babysitter (2017 film)|The Babysitter]]''. The finished film was acquired by [[Netflix]] in December 2016, and was released on Friday, October 13, 2017.<ref name=\"released\">{{cite news |url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/mcg-babysitter-netflix-new-line-bella-thorne-1201939879/ |title=McG's \u2018The Babysitter\u2019 Moves to Netflix From New Line |last1=Kroll |first1=Justin  |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=2016-12-12 |accessdate=2017-09-09}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Lewis starred in the horror mystery film ''[[Summer of 84]]'', opposite [[Graham Verchere]], [[Rich Sommer]] and [[Tiera Skovbye]];<ref>{{cite news |url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3446344/mad-men-riverdale-stars-head-back-summer-84/ |title=\u201cMad Men\u201d and \u201cRiverdale\u201d Stars Head Back to the \u2018Summer of \u201984\u2019|last=Squires|first=John|work=Bloody Disgusting|date=2017-07-12|accessdate=2018-12-06}}</ref> and in the Netflix family film ''[[The Christmas Chronicles]]'', as Teddy Pierce, alongside [[Kurt Russell]] as Santa Claus, and [[Kimberly Williams-Paisley]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=V0xv99h17QE |title=The Christmas Chronicles Teaser Netflix |website=Netflix YouTube channel|accessdate=2018-10-10}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, he co-starred in the horror film ''[[I See You (2019 film)|I See You]]''. He is set to reprise his roles as Cole in the horror-comedy ''[[The Babysitter 2]]'' and Teddy in ''The Christmas Chronicles 2'', both Netflix sequels.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n=== Film ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Deliverance Creek]]''\n| Caleb Barlow\n| TV film\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2015\n| ''[[Demolition (2015 film)|Demolition]]''\n| Chris Moreno\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Point Break (2015 film)|Point Break]]''\n| Young Johnny Utah\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| data-sort-value=\"Babysitter 1, The\" | ''[[The Babysitter (2017 film)|The Babysitter]]''\n| Cole\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2018\n| ''[[Summer of 84]]''\n| Tommy \"Eats\" Eaton \n|\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"Christmas Chronicles, The\" |''[[The Christmas Chronicles]]''\n| Teddy Pierce\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n|''[[I See You (2019 film)|I See You]]''\n| Connor Harper\n|\n|-\n| TBA\n| data-sort-value=\"Babysitter 2, The\" | ''[[The Babysitter 2]]''{{thinsp}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/judah-lewis-mcg-returning-sequel-netflix-horror-flick-babysitter-1243455|title=Judah Lewis Returning for Sequel to Netflix Horror Flick 'The Babysitter' (Exclusive)|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first=Borys|last=Kit|date=September 25, 2019|accessdate=October 18, 2019}}</ref>\n| Cole\n| Post-production\n|}\n\n=== Television ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[CSI: Cyber]]''\n| Denny Metz\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Game of Silence (U.S. TV series)|Game of Silence]]''\n| Young Gil Harris\n| 6 episodes\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name}}\n\n{{US-actor-stub}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lewis, Judah}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:2001 births]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:American male child actors]]\n[[Category:American people of Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actor}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Judah Lewis\n| image              = Judah Lewis on BTVR.jpg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = Lewis discusses ''[[Demolition (2015 film)|Demolition]]'' in 2016\n| birth_date         = {{circa|{{Birth based on age as of date|17|2018|11|22}}}}<ref name=\"thr\">{{cite news |title=Judah Lewis on Working With Kurt Russell for 'Christmas Chronicles' and Why It Isn't Just a \"Kids Movie\" |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/judah-lewis-discusses-working-kurt-russell-christmas-chronicles-1163160 |accessdate=19 March 2020 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |language=en}}</ref>\n| birth_place        = \n| nationality        = American\n| occupation         = Actor\n| years_active       = 2014\u2013present\n| known_for          = \n| height             = \n| notable_works      = {{plainlist|\n* ''[[Demolition (2015 film)|Demolition]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[The Babysitter (2017 film)|The Babysitter]]'' (2017)\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Judah Lewis''' (born {{circa|{{Birth based on age as of date|17|2018|11|22|noage=1}}}})<ref name=\"thr\" /> is an American actor, known for roles in the films ''[[The Babysitter (2017 film)|The Babysitter]]'', ''[[Summer of 84]]'', ''[[Deliverance Creek]]'' and ''[[Demolition (2015 film)|Demolition]]'', and a recurring role in the 2016 television series ''[[Game of Silence (U.S. TV series)|Game of Silence]]''.\n\n== Life and career ==\nLewis is the son of Hara and Mark Lewis, who are acting teachers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thejewishnews.com/2017/10/11/33207/|title=Celebrity Jews, Hollywood, Movies and more |last1=Bloom|first1=Nate|work=The Jewish News|date=2017-10-11 |accessdate=2019-11-10}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2015, Lewis was among the six actors who screen tested for the lead role (which went to [[Tom Holland (actor)|Tom Holland]]) in the 2017 reboot film ''[[Spider-Man: Home